<p>Order processing includes picking, packing, packing materials, label generation, and handoff to the carrier. There are no hidden surcharges for &ldquo;system access&rdquo; or &ldquo;account management.&rdquo;</p>

<p><strong>Example calculation:</strong> An online store shipping 100 orders per day at the 50&ndash;199 tier (22 UAH per order) over 22 working days spends 48,400 UAH (~$1,100) on order processing, plus storage. Compare that to the cost of renting warehouse space, hiring a packer, buying materials, and losing 90+ hours per month of your own time. At this volume, outsourcing is almost always cheaper &mdash; before you even account for the time savings.</p>

<h2 id="ukraine">Fulfillment in Ukraine: why it is 50% cheaper than EU</h2>

<p>If you are an international seller exploring Eastern European logistics, or a Ukrainian seller considering whether local 3PL makes sense, this section is for you.</p>

<p>Ukraine has quietly developed a sophisticated e-commerce logistics sector. The country had over 200,000 active online stores before 2022, and the number has grown since as businesses digitized rapidly. Domestic carriers like Nova Poshta operate 12,000+ branches &mdash; more pickup points per capita than most Western European countries &mdash; with next-day delivery across the entire country.</p>

<p>Here is why fulfillment in Ukraine offers exceptional value:</p>

<p><strong>Labor costs.</strong> Average warehouse wages in Ukraine are 4&ndash;5x lower than in Poland, Germany, or the Czech Republic. This directly translates into per-order processing fees that Western European 3PLs simply cannot match. MTP Group charges $0.41&ndash;$0.59 per order. A comparable service in Germany runs $2.50&ndash;$4.00.</p>

<p><strong>Warehouse costs.</strong> Industrial real estate near Kyiv costs a fraction of what you would pay in Warsaw, not to mention Berlin or Amsterdam. Storage at MTP Group is approximately $14.77 per cubic meter per month. In Western Europe, the same space costs $40&ndash;$70.</p>

<p><strong>Technology parity.</strong> Ukrainian fulfillment operators run the same WMS software, barcode scanning systems, and API integrations as their European counterparts. The technology gap is effectively zero. MTP Group integrates with all major Ukrainian marketplaces (Rozetka, Prom.ua, Kasta) as well as international platforms, CRM systems like KeyCRM and SalesDrive, and shipping APIs.</p>

<p><strong>Scale.</strong> MTP Group alone processes <strong>60,000+ shipments per month</strong> across <strong>3,700 m&sup2;</strong> of warehouse space near Kyiv, serving <strong>150+ active clients</strong>. Peak capacity reaches <strong>6,000 orders per day</strong>. This is not a startup &mdash; it is a decade-old operation with the infrastructure to prove it.</p>

<p>For sellers targeting the Ukrainian domestic market, there is no reason to look elsewhere. For international sellers exploring nearshoring or cost optimization, Ukraine represents one of the most cost-effective 3PL locations in Europe.</p>

<h2 id="checklist">Choosing a fulfillment partner: the checklist</h2>

<p>Not all 3PLs are equal. Use this checklist when evaluating providers &mdash; whether in Ukraine or anywhere else.</p>

<ol>
<li><strong>Transparent pricing.</strong> If the provider hides their rates behind a &ldquo;Request a quote&rdquo; form with no published numbers, treat it as a red flag. Good operators publish their pricing openly because they are confident in their value.</li>

<li><strong>WMS with real-time dashboard.</strong> You should be able to log in at any time and see current stock levels, today&rsquo;s shipments, pending orders, and return status. If the reporting is a weekly Excel file, keep looking.</li>

<li><strong>API integrations.</strong> The provider should connect directly to your sales channels (website, marketplaces, CRM) via API. Manual order entry means human errors and delays.</li>

<li><strong>Processing speed with a number.</strong> Ask &ldquo;What is your average pick-and-pack time per order?&rdquo; A good answer is 30&ndash;60 seconds. Anything vague like &ldquo;same-day shipping&rdquo; without specifics may hide inefficiency.</li>

<li><strong>Carrier pickup frequency.</strong> One carrier pickup per day means any order placed after late morning ships tomorrow. Four pickups per day means a 14:00 cutoff for same-day dispatch. This directly affects your customer satisfaction and marketplace ratings.</li>

<li><strong>Backup infrastructure.</strong> Does the warehouse have generators? Backup internet? What happens during a power outage? In some markets this is nice-to-have. In Ukraine, it is non-negotiable. More on this below.</li>

<li><strong>Returns workflow.</strong> Ask how returns are handled. Is there photographic documentation? Can you set rules for what gets restocked vs. quarantined? Returns are 20&ndash;30% of e-commerce volume &mdash; a sloppy returns process will cost you.</li>

<li><strong>Scalability proof.</strong> Ask for peak-season numbers. How many orders can they handle per day at maximum capacity? What happened during their last Black Friday? A provider that handles 6,000 orders per day at peak will not break a sweat at your 200.</li>

<li><strong>References with numbers.</strong> &ldquo;We are the best&rdquo; means nothing. &ldquo;Client X grew from 12 to 72 orders per day in 3 months after switching to us&rdquo; is a verifiable claim with substance.</li>

<li><strong>Trial period.</strong> A confident provider will offer a 1-month trial. If they insist on a 12-month contract before you have shipped a single order, that tells you something about their retention rate.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="power">Power resilience: the Ukraine question</h2>

<p>Let us address this directly, because it is the first thing any international client asks.</p>

<p>Since February 2022, Ukraine has experienced periodic power grid disruptions due to the ongoing conflict. For any logistics operation, electricity is not optional &mdash; WMS systems need servers, barcode scanners need charging, lights need to be on, and climate control must function. A fulfillment center without power is a warehouse full of boxes that nobody can process.</p>

<p>This is precisely why <strong>power resilience is the single most important evaluation criterion</strong> when choosing a Ukrainian 3PL.</p>

<p>Here is what MTP Group has in place:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>3 industrial generators</strong> &mdash; not portable units from a hardware store, but industrial-grade diesel generators capable of powering the full warehouse operation indefinitely.</li>
<li><strong>2 independent fiber-optic ISPs</strong> &mdash; if one provider goes down, internet switches to the second automatically.</li>
<li><strong>Starlink satellite connection</strong> &mdash; a third-layer backup that operates independently of ground infrastructure entirely.</li>
<li><strong>Result: zero operational downtime since February 2022.</strong> Not one day. Not one shift. Orders have shipped every single working day without interruption for over four years.</li>
</ul>

<p>This level of preparedness is not universal. Many smaller operators in Ukraine do not have this infrastructure and have experienced significant disruptions. The difference between a provider with triple-redundant power and one with a single generator is the difference between a reliable business partner and a liability.</p>

<p>When evaluating any Ukrainian 3PL, ask: <em>&ldquo;How many days of operational downtime have you had since 2022?&rdquo;</em> The answer will tell you everything you need to know.</p>

<h2 id="case">Case study: 6x growth in 3 months</h2>

<p><strong>Client:</strong> Carter&rsquo;s &mdash; a children&rsquo;s clothing brand selling through its own website and multiple Ukrainian marketplaces.</p>

<p><strong>Before MTP Group:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>12 orders per day</li>
<li>Owner personally handling all packing and shipping</li>
<li>3&ndash;4 hours per day spent on logistics</li>
<li>Per-order cost (including time, materials, travel): approximately 30 UAH (~$0.68)</li>
<li>No time or energy left for marketing, product expansion, or marketplace optimization</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>After switching to MTP Group fulfillment:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>72 orders per day</strong> within 3 months &mdash; a 6x increase</li>
<li><strong>Per-order cost dropped to 14 UAH (~$0.32)</strong> &mdash; a 53% reduction</li>
<li><strong>90+ hours per month</strong> freed from logistics tasks</li>
<li>All time redirected to advertising, product sourcing, and marketplace ranking</li>
</ul>

<p>The growth was not caused by fulfillment alone &mdash; but fulfillment made it possible. When the owner stopped being a warehouse worker and became a marketer, revenue followed. The lower per-unit cost at higher volumes created a virtuous cycle: more orders meant cheaper fulfillment, which meant higher margins, which funded more advertising, which brought more orders.</p>

<p>This pattern repeats across virtually every client that transitions from self-fulfillment to outsourced 3PL. The constraint is almost never demand &mdash; it is operational capacity. Remove the logistics bottleneck, and growth happens naturally.</p>

